50|$|In some jurisdictions a <b>commutation</b> <b>of</b> <b>sentence</b> may be conditional, {{meaning that}} the convicted person may be {{required}} to abide by specified conditions or may lose the benefit of the commutation. The conditions must be lawful and reasonable, and will typically expire when the convicted completes any remaining portion of his or her sentence. For example, the pardon may be conditioned upon the person's being a law-abiding citizen, such that if the beneficiary of the commutation commits a new crime before the condition expires the original sentence may be restored.|$|E
